05608nam a22009255i 9780520940376DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20042004cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209403767 a10.1525/97805209403762doi  a(DE-B1597)520331  a(OCoLC)55531932  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPS1332 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a818/.409aB2221 aLystra, Karen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDangerous Intimacy :bThe Untold Story of Mark Twain’s Final Years /cKaren Lystra. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (363 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note On Names -- t1. Mark Twain—And Sam’S Women -- t2. Heartbreak -- t3. Rearranging The Household -- t4. Looking For Love -- t5. A Pact With The Devil -- t6. Life In The Sanitarium -- t7. Someone To Love Him And Pet Him -- t8. A Viper To Her Bosom -- t9. Innocence At Home -- t10. Stormfield -- t11. An American Lear -- t12. Illusions Of Love -- t13. Unraveling -- t14. The Exile Returns -- t15. Confrontation -- t16. A Formidable Adversary -- t17. False Exoneration -- t18. The Funniest Joke In The World -- t19. Melting Marble With Ice -- t20. The End Of My Autobiography -- tEpilogue: How Little One May Tell -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe last phase of Mark Twain's life is sadly familiar: Crippled by losses and tragedies, America's greatest humorist sank into a deep and bitter depression. It is also wrong. This book recovers Twain's final years as they really were—lived in the shadow of deception and prejudice, but also in the light of the author's unflagging energy and enthusiasm. Dangerous Intimacy relates the story of how, shortly after his wife's death in 1904, Twain basked in the attentions of Isabel Lyon, his flirtatious—and calculating—secretary. Lyon desperately wanted to marry her boss, who was almost thirty years her senior. She managed to exile Twain's youngest daughter, Jean, who had epilepsy. With the help of Twain's assistant, Ralph Ashcroft, who fraudulently acquired power of attorney over the author's finances, Lyon nearly succeeded in assuming complete control over Twain's life and estate. Fortunately, Twain recognized the plot being woven around him just in time. So rife with twists and turns as to defy belief, the story nonetheless comes to undeniable, vibrant life in the letters and diaries of those who witnessed it firsthand: Katy the housekeeper, Jean, Lyon, and others whose own distinctive, perceptive, often amusing voices take us straight into the heart of the Clemens household. Just as Twain extricated himself from the lies, prejudice, and self-delusion that almost turned him into an American Lear, so Karen Lystra liberates the author's last decade from a century of popular misunderstanding. In this gripping book we at last see how, late in life, this American icon discovered a deep kinship with his youngest child and continued to explore the precarious balance of love and pain that is one of the trademarks of his work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAuthors, Americany19th centuryvBiography. 0aAuthors, Americany20th centuryvBiography. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  a19th century american culture.  a19th century american literature.  aamerican literature.  aamerican studies.  aclara clemens.  adaughter.  adeath.  adeception.  adepression.  aembezzlement.  aepilepsy.  afamily drama.  afamily.  afinancial impropriety.  agrief.  aheartfelt.  ahumorist.  ainstitutionalized.  aisabel lyon.  ajean cleme